Regression and model validation

Reading and exploring structures and dimension of the data

In this excercise I first read the data (learning2014.csv) that was created in the data wrankling part of the excercise. For this I used read.csv()-commmand that reads the data. To explore structure and dimension of the data, I used following dim(learning2014) str(learning2014) commands. Dimension command showed that data consisted of 166 observations and seven variables. Stucture command showed the structure of the data. Seven variables were Gender, Age, Attitude, Seep, Stra, Surf, Points. Gender consist of two level factor (F=1 or M=2). Age is showed as an years. Attitude, deep, stra and surf are numeric factors. Points -variable indicates the exam points of the person. I used following scripts:

read.csv(learning2014.csv)

dim(learning2014) str(learning2014)

Graphical overview of the datas

Next I made a graphical overview of the data. For that I used fast plotting (pairs()), which draws all possible scater plot from the column of a data frame. Results are then showed in a scatter plot matrix. In this analysis gender is excluded from the plot. However, gender is showed in different colours.I used following script:

pairs(learning2014 [-1], col = learning2014$gender)

This fast plotting is however a bit hard to go through. Therefore, I made scatterplot (ggplot) where point variable is compared to attitude. Gender is showed here in red and blue For this I used following script:

p1 <- ggplot(learning2014, aes(x = attitude, y = points, col = gender)) p2 <- p1 + geom_point() p3 <- p2 + geom_smooth(method = lm) p3

In addition I did ggpairs-plot p <- ggpairs(learning2014, mapping = aes(col = gender, alpha = 0.3), lower = list(combo = wrap(facethist, bins = 20)))

Summary of the variables

Next I wanted to have summary of the variables. For this I used following script:

summary(learning2014)

Summary and ggplot shows that there were more women (110) than men (56) in a data. Age of the persons were between 17-55 years, mean was 25.51 and median 22.00. In attitude variable values were between 1.400-5.000 (average 3.680, meadian 3.667). In deep questions variable values were between 1.583-4.917 (mean 3.680, median 3.667).In strategic questions variable values were between 1.250-5.000 (mean 3.121, median 3.118). In surface questions variable values were between 1.583-4.333 (mean 2.787, median 2.833).In exam points values were between 7-33 (mean 22.72, median 23.00).

Regression models

In regression modeling you can estimate the relationship between dependet variable (target) and one or more independent variables (explanatory variables). If there is more than one explanatory variables, it is called multiple regression. I used exam point as an target variable and explanatory variables were attitude, stra, surf. In this excercise I used following script:

ggpairs(learning2014, lower = list(combo = wrap(facethist, bins = 20))) my_model1 <- lm(points ~ attitude + stra + surf, data = learning2014)

Summary of the fitted model

summary(my_model1)

From the data we can see that p value of Stra and surf is less than 0.05, which means that there is no significant differences.Therefore they are deleted from the the variable and model is fitted again without them using following script:

my_model1.2 <- lm(points ~ attitude, data = learning2014) summary(my_model1.2)

Diagnostic plots

Finally I did diagnostic plots (Residual vs Fitted, Normal Q-Q, Residual vs Leverage) using following script:

par(mfrow = c(2,2)) plot(my_model1.2, which = c(1,2,5))

FOllowing variables were compared to high/low alcohol consumption

Sex, failures, goout, health

Personal hypothesis behind these chosen variables

Sex: There are more men than women that use alcohol in high consumption age: Students that are older use more alcohol than younger students goout: Students that go out with friends have high consumption of alcohol health: Students that have high alcohol consumption have lower health status

m <- glm(high_use ~ failures + absences + sex, data = alc, family = "binomial")

Prediction of the probability of high_use

probabilities <- predict(m, type = "response")
alc <- mutate(alc, probability = probabilities)
alc <- mutate(alc, prediction = probability > 0.5)

Next LDA (bi)plot was drawn.

lda.arrows <- function(x, myscale = 1, arrow_heads = 0.1, color = "purple", tex = 0.75, choices = c(1,2)){
  heads <- coef(x)
  arrows(x0 = 0, y0 = 0, 
         x1 = myscale * heads[,choices[1]], 
         y1 = myscale * heads[,choices[2]], col=color, length = arrow_heads)
  text(myscale * heads[,choices], labels = row.names(heads), 
       cex = tex, col=color, pos=3)
}
classes <- as.numeric(train$crime)
plot(lda.fit, dimen = 2, col = classes, pch = classes)
lda.arrows(lda.fit, myscale = 1)

Prediction of classes with the LDA model on the test data

Crime categories were saved from the test set.

correct_classes <- test$crime

Then the categorical crime variable was removed from the test dataset.

test <- dplyr::select(test, -crime)

Then classes were predicted with the LDA model on the test data. Then table of the corrected classes and the predicted ones were created using cross tabulare.

lda.pred <- predict(lda.fit, newdata = test)
table(correct = correct_classes, predicted = lda.pred$class)
##           predicted
## correct    low med_low med_high high
##   low       15      13        1    0
##   med_low    3      15        2    0
##   med_high   1       7       14    2
##   high       0       0        1   28

This table shows that prediction of class high was right. In classes low and med low there were few events (5 in low categories and 8 in the med low categories) that were not predicted right. Predicton with med_high class was not good because there were quite many events in med_low class (13) and one in high class.

Next K-means dataset was run on the dataset

km <-kmeans(boston_sca, centers = 3)
pairs(boston_sca, col = km$cluster)

Then investigation of the optimal number of clusters was performed.

library(ggplot2)
set.seed(123)
k_max <- 10
twcss <- sapply(1:k_max, function(k){kmeans(boston_sca, k)$tot.withinss})
qplot(x = 1:k_max, y = twcss, geom = 'line')

Based on the graph above, the optimal number of clusters is two because the total WCSS changes radically in that point. Therefore the the algorithm was run again using two clusters.

km <-kmeans(Boston, centers = 2)
pairs(boston_sca, col = km$cluster)
